<p><b>Ivan Illich</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[ɪˈvɑn ˈɪlɪtʃ]</a></span><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) (<a href="/wiki/Vienna" title="Vienna">Vienna</a>, <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1926-09-04"><a href="/wiki/September_4" title="September 4">4 September</a> <a href="/wiki/1926" title="1926">1926</a></span> – <a href="/wiki/Bremen" title="Bremen">Bremen</a>, <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2002-12-02"><a href="/wiki/December_2" title="December 2">2 December</a> <a href="/wiki/2002" title="2002">2002</a></span>) was an <a href="/wiki/Austria" title="Austria">Austrian</a> philosopher, social critic, and <a href="/wiki/Defrocking" title="Defrocking">defrocked</a> <a href="/wiki/Roman_Catholic" title="Roman Catholic" class="mw-redirect">Roman Catholic</a> priest. He authored a series of critiques of the institutions of contemporary western culture and their effects of the provenance and practice of education, medicine, work, energy use, and economic development.</p>
